<P>
 STREET SMARTS: For the first time since 1933, the state has some surprises in 
its driver's test. Prepare to take a spin on the freeway, or properly navigate 
your car into a space in a parking lot. . . . Although the DMV is giving the 
new test across much of Southern California, it'll be another year before it 
pops up in Ventura County. With heavy traffic and more wackos on the road, the 
DMV hopes it'll improve safety. "We are trying to make the test more relative 
to current conditions," says regional manager John Raymond. 
</P>
<P>
 UNITED THEY BUY: To pare costs, United Airlines is being sold to its employees 
(A1). Pilots, ground crews and office workers will give up billions of dollars 
in wages and benefits for a majority share of the company. . . . The purchase 
should not affect United Express, one of the two airlines that service Oxnard 
Airport. United Express is owned by Mesa Airlines, which has a contract to fly 
into Oxnard. "Nothing is going to change," said John Reber, a United Express 
agent. "Seven flights daily to Los Angeles." 
</P>
<P>
 HIT THE TRAIL: Ron Blakemore has a plan to preserve at least a sliver of 
Ventura County's natural splendor: He's developed a latticework of more than 
200 miles of off-road trails that would crisscross the county (B4). . . . Even 
if urban sprawl gobbles up most of the remaining open space, hikers, bikers and 
equestrians could trek from Simi Valley to the Santa Barbara County line. . . . 
Blakemore publicly unveils his plans tonight in Simi Valley. 
</P>
<P>
 RISKY BUSINESS: Sheriff Larry Carpenter gets lots of money from the county 
supervisors, including most of the windfall from the Proposition 172 half-cent 
sales tax. . . . But on Tuesday, Carpenter threw his support behind the cities' 
demands for a portion of the tax windfall (B1). "I cannot believe Carpenter is 
doing this," said Supervisor Maggie Kildee. Five of those cities pay the 
sheriff millions to provide police protection. But he has yet to nail down this 
year's budget from the county. He goes before the supervisors today. 
</P>
