<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: OJAI; CABLE TV FIRM TOLD TO REDUCE RATES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JASON GRANT 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Ojai City Council ordered its local cable company Tuesday to lower its 
basic monthly rates by 18 cents and refund money to customers who the city says 
have been overcharged since September. 
</P>
<P>
 But the parent company of Ventura County Cablevision, Western Communications, 
said it will appeal the council's ruling with the Federal Communications 
Commission, which can reverse the council's decision. 
</P>
<P>
 Ojai officials and Cablevision representatives disagree over the amount that 
cable rates should have been lowered to comply with new FCC regulations 
implemented last September. Ojai officials say the current monthly rate of 
$10.62 for basic cable service should have been lowered to $10.44, but 
Cablevision officials say the rate is correct. 
</P>
<P>
 The refund would amount to about $7,000 divided among about 3,000 subscribers. 
</P>
<P>
 Ojai City Manager Andrew Belknap said FCC regulations change frequently, 
leading to differing interpretations of how the regulations affect billing. 
</P>
<P>
 Laurie DeVarney, a consultant hired by Ojai and principal of Laurel 
Communications Group, said her firm and Western Communications disagree on the 
method for calculating one part of the overall equation for arriving at the 
cable rate. 
</P>
<P>
 DeVarney said her firm concluded that the portion of the rate formula in 
question is correct. But Johnnie Giles, director of government affairs for 
Western Communications, said his company believes that part of the formula is 
wrong. 
</P>
<P>
 "We felt that it was a basic flaw in the form," Giles said. "Many operators 
filed clarifications on this very item."  
</P>
<P>
 Also Tuesday, the council voted to raise the franchise fee on cable bills for 
Ojai residents from 3% to 5%, amounting to a monthly increase that would amount 
to no more than 40 cents. Belknap said DeVarney suggested the hike because the 
city was not recouping costs it incurred implementing FCC regulations. 
</P>
<P>
 On Friday, a new round of cable rates will take effect, further lowering the 
monthly rate to $10.05. JASON GRANT 
</P>
</TEXT>
