<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VALLEY FOCUS: AGOURA HILLS; EXEMPTIONS OFFERED FOR NEW UTILITY TAX 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KURT PITZER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Elderly and low-income Agoura Hills residents may apply for exemptions from 
the city's newly adopted utility tax beginning this week. 
</P>
<P>
 The tax, approved last month by the City Council, places a 4% tax on the use 
of electricity, gas and telephone service. 
</P>
<P>
 "The purpose of the exemption, is to assist people who may have difficulty 
paying the tax," City Manager Terry Matz said. 
</P>
<P>
 Eligible for the exemption are Agoura Hills heads of household who are at 
least 62 years old and receive supplemental security income, and households 
with income ranging from $17,650 for one person to $33,250 total for eight 
people. 
</P>
<P>
 According to 1990 census figures, 451 households in Agoura Hills have an 
income of less than $35,000. 
</P>
<P>
 Residents who feel they may be eligible should contact Agoura Hills City Hall 
between 7 a.m. and 6 p.m., Monday through Thursday. KURT PITZER 
</P>
</TEXT>
