<HEADLINE>
<P>
A LONG AND VARIED HISTORY OF VISIONS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARY ROURKE, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The history of heavenly apparitions in the Roman Catholic Church is long and 
rich. While most reports are never officially sanctioned by the church, a 
handful have been approved as authentic. 
</P>
<P>
 Many of these apparitions have certain things in common: the Virgin Mary is 
said to appear, alone or with Jesus. Most often, it is the powerless and 
impoverished who say they have seen her. She appears to them in nature -- on a 
hillside, in a grove or in a grotto. And she delivers messages meant for the 
world. Usually, the messages contain some good news and some bad. 
</P>
<P>
 Of course, no apparition has ever been "proved" by scientific standards, but 
the sites where visions have been reported attract millions of visitors. And 
thousands have claimed to be cured, physically or spiritually, as a result. 
</P>
<P>
 In the Americas, Our Lady of Guadalupe is the premiere pilgrim site. On Dec. 
9, 1531, a peasant named Juan Diego told the local bishop that he met the 
Virgin in the hills near what is now Mexico City. She asked him to have a 
church built in her honor, but the bishop wanted proof. Legend has it that Juan 
Diego opened his cloak to show the Virgin's image impressed upon it. And the 
building of a church, now Our Lady of Guadalupe basilica in Mexico City, began. 
</P>
<P>
 France captured world attention in the 19th Century when four separate visions 
of the Virgin were accepted as authentic by the church. Over a period of 41 
years, she was said to appear to a nun in Paris, two children in LaSalette in 
Southern France, and four children on a farm in Pontmain, near the German 
border. 
</P>
<P>
 But events at Lourdes, in southwestern France, eclipsed them all. The country 
girl Bernadette Soubirous was not yet a teen-ager in February, 1858, when she 
told of seeing the Virgin in a grotto. Bernadette later described how she was 
directed to uncover an underground spring of water with her hands.  
</P>
<P>
 Since then, thousands have claimed to be healed by that water. A 
church-coordinated medical board tracks health records to determine whether the 
cures can be explained by natural, rather than supernatural, causes. The vast 
majority have been judged to be normal cures. 
</P>
<P>
 In 1917, attention swiveled to Fatima, Portugal, when three shepherd children 
reported seeing the Virgin once each month, from May through October. They 
shared messages they said she gave them, asking people to fast and pray. One 
message promised, "If they listen to my requests, Russia will be converted and 
there will be peace." 
</P>
<P>
 That was the good news from Fatima. The rest of it was awful. Unchecked 
disease, massive death and destruction, and fire falling from the sky were 
among the horrific predictions. 
</P>
<P>
 Some say the messages of Fatima foretell of the millennium, the end of time. 
Others say it predicted the spread of communism through the 20th Century. 
</P>
<P>
 Interest in the dark messages of Fatima has peaked again lately, perhaps in 
part because we are so close to the end of this century. "The end of time as we 
know it has always been part of a Christian world view," notes Anne Taves, 
professor of Christian church history at Claremont School of Theology. "It was 
a widespread belief in Greco-Roman world, and a strong motif in the early 
Christian church." 
</P>
<P>
 Some suggest that the calendar may even help explain the recent rise in 
reports of apparitions. 
</P>
<P>
 "The millennium is seen as a critical time," says Robert Ellwood, professor of 
Comparative Religion at University of Southern California. "There is a sense 
that we're coming to the end of an age, and changes are probably imminent. 
There is a lot of anxiety in the air. This opens a crack for what is outside 
the scientific and predictable." 
</P>
<P>
 Some religion scholars with a scientific bent suggest that too many travelers 
to pilgrim sites fall through that crack. Among pilgrims and some other 
Catholics, stories abound about suns that spin in the sky, rosaries that turn 
gold and physical ailments that miraculously disappear. 
</P>
<P>
 "This is magical thinking," scolds Gerald Larue, head of the Committee for 
Scientific Examination of Religion and Emeritus Professor of Religion at USC. 
He has traveled to apparition sites in California and come away unconvinced. 
"These claims need to be tested," he says. "Critical thinking is the road to 
progress." 
</P>
<P>
 Recently, a woman told Larue that her silver rosary turned gold while she was 
on a pilgrimage. His advice? "Dip it in Tarn-X. See if it's just tarnished 
beads." 
</P>
<P>
 She refused, he says. 
</P>
<P>
 That the church hierarchy is skeptical toward visions, voices and other 
supernatural activity does not surprise Sister Bridget Mary Meehan of Falls 
Church, Va. "The mystical is threatening because the hierarchy can't control 
it," says Meehan, who studied visionaries through history for her book, 
"Praying With Passionate Women," due out in January from Crossroads Press. 
</P>
<P>
 "Their white-male perspective is not open to the mystical. They're into the 
logical, not emotional. Apparitions are relational and powerful. Not 
analytical." 
</P>
<P>
 Sidney Callahan, professor of Psychology at Mercy College in Dobbs Ferry, 
N.Y., agrees that the rise in reported apparitions today could reflect greater 
openness. But, she cautions, "The price you pay for mysticism is, you have to 
live with superstitiousness." 
</P>
</TEXT>
